.78","primary_url_label":"NPG Catalog of American Portraits"},"birth":{"year":1778,"month":3,"day":12,"city":"Wethersfield","county":"Hartford County","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1857,"month":5,"day":24,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"artworks":["ART018"],"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"She and her future husband shared Litchfield","detail":"Elizabeth's portrait, painted by Gerritt Schipper in 1805, now hangs at the Yale University Art Gallery. She and Jonathan had eleven children, six of whom graduated from Yale — a record that prompted the Yale obituary of one son to call them 'a family of six brothers, all graduates of this college.' She was the daughter of Moses Tryon, a family name that echoes through her children: Tryon Edwards (HD2632, the theologian) was named directly for her family. She died in 1857, the year Abraham Lincoln began his presidential campaign, having lived through the entire Early Republic. (Litchfield Historical Society; NPG Catalog of American Portraits)","body":"She attended Sarah Pierce’s Female Academy in 1794, the same year Jonathan Walter Edwards was studying at the Law School up the street — they married three years later and raised ten children. The 1909 genealogy miscopied her surname as “Lyon.”","number":1}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Elizabeth Tryon Edwards","first_name":"Elizabeth","last_name":"Edwards","maiden_name":"Tryon","middle_name":"Tryon","married_names":["Edwards"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"education":[{"school_name":"Litchfield Female Academy","dates":"1794","type":"secondary"}],"slug":"elizabeth-tryon-1778"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}